luckynawabs
Thu Jul 15, 2004 1:12 pm


-----------------------------------
There is a monkey hanging by a branch of a tree. And there is a hunter
with his gun looking for a kill. The hunter spots the monkey, takes aim
with the help of the laser pointer on the gun, and fires at the monkey.
At that very precise moment (the moment that the shot is fired), the
monkey lets go of the tree branch and starts his free fall towards the
ground. Will the monkey dodge the bullet and survive this incident?

Height of monkey from ground - h, distance of hunter from base of tree -
d, Velocity of bullet - v, and acceleration due to gravity - g. Can
assume monkey to be point object, or of height h1, whichever way you
prefer your monkeys.

The moment that the shot is fired = the time when the bullet starts its
motion, and is not to be interpreted as the time when the monkey heard
the shot. So velocity of sound does not come into play.

Good hunting

